    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9cfef69f-0ca8-4f5b-a31d-c234aa002806",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 75-year-old retired schoolteacher from Brno, Czech Republic, who lives alone in a ground-floor apartment after her husband passed away six years ago. She is a slight, somewhat stooped woman with grey hair worn neatly pinned back; her facial expression appears reduced in animation, and her voice has become noticeably softer over the past two years. She arrived at the neurology outpatient clinic accompanied by her adult daughter, walking slowly with short, shuffling steps and a tendency to lean slightly forward [SNOMED:G20, MEDLINEPLUS:G20].\n\n{patientName} first noticed a rhythmic trembling of her right hand approximately three years ago, which she initially dismissed as simple ageing. Over time the trembling spread to her right arm and jaw, and she began experiencing marked stiffness in both arms and legs as well as slowness in performing everyday tasks such as buttoning her blouse or pouring tea [MEDLINEPLUS:G20]. She also reports episodes of poor balance and one near-fall in her kitchen last month [MEDLINEPLUS:G20]. She has been increasingly troubled by difficulty swallowing her medications and problems with sleep [MEDLINEPLUS:G20].\n\nIn her spare time {patientName} enjoys tending her small balcony garden and listening to Czech folk music. She was a meticulous reader and enjoyed knitting, though she has had to give up knitting due to hand tremor [MEDLINEPLUS:G20]. She has a close circle of friends from her former school who visit regularly and she attends a seniors' day centre twice a week. Her daughter visits every weekend and has been helping increasingly with shopping and meal preparation.\n\n{patientName} appears mildly anxious, which her daughter attributes partly to a long-standing depressive tendency that has been managed medically for several years [PMID:35730513]. Cognitive function is broadly intact on brief assessment, though she occasionally has word-finding difficulties. She denies tobacco use and drinks only occasional wine at family occasions."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:f931fdee-a129-47be-9d3f-16db413556b7",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a background of well-controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus managed with metformin, and arterial hypertension treated with amlodipine. She has a history of hyperlipidaemia for which she takes atorvastatin. A diagnosis of mild recurrent depression was established approximately eight years ago and is currently treated with sertraline [PMID:35730513]; her mood has been broadly stable on this regimen, though her daughter notes increased apathy over the past year. She takes omeprazole for chronic gastro-oesophageal reflux symptoms. {patientName} was hospitalised once in 2012 for a right hip replacement following osteoarthritis, and underwent an elective cholecystectomy in 2008 for symptomatic gallstones. She is a non-smoker and reports no alcohol misuse. She has no known exposure to pesticides or industrial chemicals but spent several years teaching in an older school building, details unknown. Family history is notable for her father having had a tremor disorder in his seventies."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
